docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3208:**GlyphWeave sits at a crossroads of traditions spanning millennia — from Mesopotamian mosaic tesserae to BBS-era ANSI art packs to modern emoji copypasta on Discord.** This research identifies the aesthetic precedents, technical constraints, LLM generation strategies, and community contexts that should inform its specification. The central finding across all four research areas is that constraint-based modular composition is the unifying thread: every successful text art tradition thrives on a defined grid, a limited vocabulary, and community-driven exchange. GlyphWeave's hybrid ASCII + emoji approach would bridge two currently separate worlds — the CP437 tradition of the ANSI artscene and modern Unicode/emoji culture — a gap no existing format or tool explicitly fills.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3220:**Japanese text art** developed along a fundamentally different aesthetic axis. The first kaomoji, (^_^), was posted by Yasushi Wakabayashi on ASCII NET at 12:28 AM on June 20, 1986 — four years after Scott Fahlman's sideways Western emoticons. Kaomoji read upright and emphasize eyes over mouths, reflecting manga/anime aesthetics. On 2channel, Shift_JIS art ("AA") created a rich visual culture using proportional-width MS PGothic font rendering, producing characters like Monā (モナー) and Giko Neko that transcended their medium to become cultural icons. Shigetaka Kurita's first 176-emoji set for NTT DoCoMo's i-Mode (1999) drew directly on this kaomoji tradition, establishing the pipeline from text art to emoji that GlyphWeave reverses.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3230:The most critical finding for GlyphWeave's specification is that **LLMs are architecturally incapable of reliable freeform spatial generation** — but structured strategies can mitigate this substantially. The core problem is that tokenization destroys spatial relationships. Characters that should be vertically aligned across rows have no way to establish strong attention patterns in the token sequence.
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3303:   - `start()` — launches a daemon thread that iterates frames, calling edit_fn(message_id, frame_text) per frame, then sleeping frame_ms/1000 seconds
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3304:   - `stop()` — sets a threading.Event to stop the loop, joins the thread with 3s timeout
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3306:   - If loop=True, cycles frames forever until stop() called
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3307:   - If loop=False, plays once then stops
docs/discovery_20260329_092950.md:3316:     - Current phase text: "→ {phase}..."
